    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-03-26T01:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-03-26T01:35:00-05:00" n="587"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d587">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.6363 Amiranian/18: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merriam</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Teheran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-03-26T10:00:00+03:25"
                            >March 26, 1937—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 2 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>14. My No. 9, March 10, 9 a.m. Law granting pipe line concession, has also been
                    communicated by the Shah for execution. It was promulgated in the <hi
                        rend="italic">Official Journal</hi> of the Ministry of Justice of March. 10.
                    Law according oil concession was similarly promulgated oil March 9. Contracts
                    thus appear to be in full legal effect.</p>
                <p>Russian Government is maintaining before the Foreign Office the <pb facs="0753"
                        n="742" xml:id="pg_742"/> validity of the Koshtaria concession<note n="25"
                        xml:id="d587fn25">For text of Khoshtaria concession, March 9, 1916, see <ref
                            target="frus1920v03#pg_351">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1920, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 351</ref>.</note> as a matter of
                    principle and is also worried over the possibility of British capital
                    participation now or in the future. Hart has endeavored to satisfy the Russians
                    as to the latter and I gather that the Foreign Office is sticking to its guns on
                    both points.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Merriam</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
